# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hitac-s-810
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hitac-s-810/access-time] In computer and software systems, it is the time interval between the point where an instruction control unit initiates a call to retrieve data or a request to store data, and the point at which delivery of the data is completed or the storage is started.
[src:hitac-s-810/access-time] Note that in distributed software systems or other systems with stochastic processes, access time or latency should be measured at the *99th percentile*.
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] The consortium's bid was centered around the Class 800 and 801 high speed trains, which provided more seats, reduced journey times, and superior environmental performance than the Intercity 125 sets.
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] The bid submitted by the consortium was successful, leading to the finalising of a £4.5bn contract in mid 2012 to produce and sustain trains for both the Great Western Main Line (GWML) and East Coast Main Line (ECML).
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] Infrastructure built to fulfil the contract included a new manufacturing site at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe and multiple new depots to maintain the fleet.
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] In October 2017, the first train went into service on the GWML.
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] Agility Trains was formed in response to the Intercity Express Programme (IEP), launched by the Department for Transport (DfT) in 2005 with the initial goal of procuring a replacement for the aging Intercity 125 fleet on both the Great Western Main Line and East Coast Main Line.
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] On 16 November 2007, the DfT issued an Invitation to Tender for the IEP to three shortlisted entities: Alstom-Barclays Rail Group; Express Rail Alliance (Bombardier, Siemens, Angel Trains and Babcock & Brown); and Agility Trains.
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] Shortly after Alstom's decision to withdraw from the bidding in February 2008, British investment firm Barclays Private Equity opted to re-enter the IEP on 26 June 2008, four days before the end of the bidding process, as a partner of Hitachi and John Laing, in Agility Trains.
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] The finalised £4.5bn contract for trains for the GWML and ECML was announced in July 2012.
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] Assembly of most of the trains took place in the UK, using Japanese-built bodyshells, with a new factory being established at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe.
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] Additionally, new depots to maintain the new train fleet were also developed.
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] The first IEP train left the Kasado factory on 7 January 2015 for shipping via Kobe, In October 2017, the first train went into service on the Great Western Main Line.
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] In May 2019, the first train entered service on the East Coast Main Line between London King's Cross and Leeds.
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] Several ownership changes took place during the late 2010s and early 2020s. in March 2018, Axa announced that it would purchase half of John Laing Group's shareholding in the consortium.
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] In September 2020, John Laing Group announced that it was selling its remaining stake in Agility Trains to AIP Management in exchange for £421 million in cash.
[src:hitac-s-810/agility-trains] In November 2021, GLIL Infrastructure purchased a 30% stake in Agility Trains from Hitachi; as a result, Hitachi's stake dropped to 40 percent while GLIL and AIP owning a 30% stake each.
[src:hitac-s-810/alaxala-networks] In 2004, Alaxala Networks Corp. was originally established, as the merger between Hitachi and NEC networking hardware divisions.
[src:hitac-s-810/alaxala-networks] The name of **Alaxala** was derived from "ALL Access for eXpert and Latent Association", and more that "Ala" in Latin means "Wing", and "X" means "networking eXchange", so the company intended the two "Ala" (Hitachi and NEC) connected and collaborated by "X" tightly.
[src:hitac-s-810/alaxala-networks] The company is basically fabless company, designing the products, mostly ordering to manufacture them to Hitachi enterprise servers division factory in Hadano, Kanagawa, Japan.
[src:hitac-s-810/alaxala-networks] The company offers networking hardware products, network router and network switch etc.
[src:hitac-s-810/alaxala-networks] Alaxala products are sold and installed mostly in Japanese domestic market and for enterprises, but we can find several products at some online shopping, Amazon.com etc..
[src:hitac-s-810/alaxala-networks] The business type and scope is same as Allied Telesis, that is also the company in Japan.
[src:hitac-s-810/alaxala-networks] And they are collaborated for producing networking hardware sold in both brands.
[src:hitac-s-810/alaxala-networks] Alaxala official agencies are Hitachi, NEC, Itochu Techno-Solutions, Net One Systems, and Alaxala has contributed to offer the various networking hardware products to major communication companies in Japan, such as NTT, KDDI, Softbank, and others.
[src:hitac-s-810/alaxala-networks] On August 24, 2012, Alaxala was known that Tokyo Stock Exchange (TSE) announced that TSE core system outage happened due to the software bugs on Alaxala networking hardware.
[src:hitac-s-810/alaxala-networks] Alaxala also sponsors IT professional certifications for Alaxala products, like Cisco, Oracle, and others.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] The company name was changed from **Hitachi Astemo, Ltd.** to Astemo, Ltd. on April 1, 2025.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] Astemo was established in January 2021 as a global automotive components manufacturer through the business merger of Hitachi Automotive Systems, Keihin Corporation, Showa Corporation, and Nissin Kogyo.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] The name "Astemo" stands for "Advanced Sustainable Technologies for Mobility", reflecting the company's focus on technologies related to connected, autonomous, shared and electric mobility.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] Astemo develops automotive technologies aligned with the industry trends of connectivity, autonomous systems and electrification, with a focus on both passenger and motorcycle applications.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] Astemo's ownership structure includes major stakes from both Hitachi, Ltd. and Honda Motor Co., Ltd., each holding 40%, with JIC Capital holding the remaining 20%.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] While Astemo includes former Honda-affiliated parts manufacturers, it also maintains business relationships with Nissan Motor Co., reflecting Hitachi's historical ties to the Nissan Group.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] In December 2025, Honda announced it would acquire an additional 21% of Astemo shares from Hitachi.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] As a result, the shareholding structure of Astemo will change to 61% for Honda, 20% for JIC, and 19% for Hitachi.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] Astemo has expanded its research and development activities in electric powertrains, advanced driver-assistance systems, and in-vehicle software.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] These efforts support its strategic focus on electrification and autonomous mobility.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] The company has also pursued partnerships and vertical integration to address industry competition and supply chain challenges.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] In December 2024, the Government of Cantabria awarded the Hitachi Astemo Buelna plant a €1 million grant through SODERCAN’s competitive programme for major industrial competitiveness projects.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] The funding supports a €5 million experimental development project focused on advanced braking systems, to be completed over 18 months.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] This initiative underlines the region’s strategic support for automotive innovation and sustainability efforts.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] Astemo develops components for electric and autonomous vehicles, with a focus on integration of key systems such as power control units, motors, inverters, and software-defined vehicle platforms.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] The company also emphasizes model-based systems engineering and virtual validation to shorten development timelines and reduce prototyping costs.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] In 2023, Astemo announced a ¥15.3 billion (~US $100 million) expansion of its Berea, Kentucky plant to support its electrification business.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] In July 2025, Astemo announced a £100 million investment in its Horwich manufacturing facility in Bolton, Greater Manchester.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] The project will establish a new production line dedicated to electric vehicle (EV) inverters, making the site the only facility in the United Kingdom with this production capability.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] As of 2025, Astemo operates over 100 business sites globally, including manufacturing plants, R&D centers and regional offices across Asia, Europe and the Americas.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] Astemo's facilities span over 25 countries, including sites in Mexico, France, Brazil, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] A complete list is available on the Astemo Global Network.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] In September 2025, *CBS News* and *The Detroit News* reported that Astemo planned to establish a regional headquarters in Wixom, Michigan, as part of a $95 million investment expected to create about 200 jobs.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] Hitachi Astemo sponsors Team Penske in NTT IndyCar Series in the U.S.A.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] Astemo also sponsors Real Racing in the Super GT GT500 class and S.I.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] RACING in the MFJ All Japan Road Race Championship Series.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] Astemo owns the Japanese women's volleyball team "Hitachi Astemo Rivale" and sponsors Mie Honda Heat, a Japanese rugby union team based in Suzuka City.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] On December 21, 2021, Hitachi Astemo admitted to falsifying inspection data on brake and suspension components.
[src:hitac-s-810/astemo] Over 50,000 instances of improper testing were identified, dating back to 2003.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] A **bipolar junction transistor** (**BJT**) is a type of transistor that uses both electrons and electron holes as charge carriers.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In contrast, a unipolar transistor, such as a field-effect transistor (FET), uses only one kind of charge carrier.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] A bipolar transistor allows a small current injected at one of its terminals to control a much larger current between the remaining two terminals, making the device capable of amplification or switching.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] BJTs use two p–n junctions between two semiconductor types, n-type and p-type, which are regions in a single crystal of material.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The junctions can be made in several different ways, such as changing the doping of the semiconductor material as it is grown, by depositing metal pellets to form alloy junctions, or by such methods as diffusion of n-type and p-type doping substances into the crystal.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The superior predictability and performance of junction transistors quickly displaced the original point-contact transistor.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Diffused transistors, along with other components, are elements of integrated circuits for analog and digital functions.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Hundreds of bipolar junction transistors can be made in one circuit at a very low cost.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Bipolar transistor integrated circuits were the main active devices of a generation of mainframe and minicomputers, but computer systems now use complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) integrated circuits relying on the field-effect transistor (FET).
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Bipolar transistors are still used for amplification of signals, switching, and in mixed-signal integrated circuits using BiCMOS.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Specialized types are used for high voltage and high current switches, or for radio-frequency (RF) amplifiers.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The bipolar point-contact transistor was invented in December 1947 at the Bell Telephone Laboratories by John Bardeen and Walter Brattain under the direction of William Shockley.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The junction version known as the bipolar junction transistor (BJT), invented by Shockley in 1948, was for three decades the device of choice in the design of discrete and integrated circuits.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The germanium transistor was more common in the 1950s and 1960s but has a greater tendency to exhibit thermal runaway.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Since germanium p-n junctions have a lower forward bias than silicon, germanium transistors turn on at lower voltage.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Various methods of manufacturing bipolar transistors were developed.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] BJTs exist as PNP and NPN types, based on the doping types of the three main terminal regions.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] An NPN transistor comprises two semiconductor junctions that share a thin p-doped region, and a PNP transistor comprises two semiconductor junctions that share a thin n-doped region.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] N-type means doped with impurities (such as phosphorus or arsenic) that provide mobile electrons, while p-type means doped with impurities (such as boron) that provide holes that readily accept electrons.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Charge flow in a BJT is due to diffusion of charge carriers (electrons and holes) across a junction between two regions of different charge carrier concentration.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The regions of a BJT are called *emitter*, *base*, and *collector*.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] A discrete transistor has three leads for connection to these regions.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Typically, the emitter region is heavily doped compared to the other two layers, and the collector is doped more lightly (typically ten times lighter) than the base.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] By design, most of the BJT collector current is due to the flow of charge carriers injected from a heavily doped emitter into the base where they are minority carriers (electrons in NPNs, holes in PNPs) that diffuse toward the collector, so BJTs are classified as *minority-carrier devices*.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In typical operation, the base–emitter junction is forward biased, which means that the p-doped side of the junction is at a more positive potential than the n-doped side, and the base–collector junction is reverse biased.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] When forward bias is applied to the base–emitter junction, the equilibrium between the thermally generated carriers and the repelling electric field of the emitter depletion region is disturbed.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] This allows thermally excited carriers (electrons in NPNs, holes in PNPs) to inject from the emitter into the base region.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] These carriers create a diffusion current through the base from the region of high concentration near the emitter toward the region of low concentration near the collector.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] To minimize the fraction of carriers that recombine before reaching the collector–base junction, the transistor's base region must be thin enough that carriers can diffuse across it in much less time than the semiconductor's minority-carrier lifetime.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Having a lightly doped base ensures recombination rates are low.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In particular, the thickness of the base must be much less than the diffusion length of the carriers.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The thin *shared* base and asymmetric collector–emitter doping are what differentiates a bipolar transistor from two *separate* diodes connected in series.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The collector–emitter current can be viewed as being controlled by the base–emitter current (current control), or by the base–emitter voltage (voltage control).
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] These views are related by the current–voltage relation of the base–emitter junction, which is the usual exponential current–voltage curve of a p–n junction (diode).
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The explanation for collector current is the concentration gradient of minority carriers in the base region.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Due to low-level injection (in which there are many fewer excess carriers than normal majority carriers) the ambipolar transport rates (in which the excess majority and minority carriers flow at the same rate) is in effect determined by the excess minority carriers.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Detailed transistor models of transistor action, such as the Gummel–Poon model, account for the distribution of this charge explicitly to explain transistor behavior more exactly.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The charge-control view easily handles phototransistors, where minority carriers in the base region are created by the absorption of photons, and handles the dynamics of turn-off, or recovery time, which depends on charge in the base region recombining.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] However, because base charge is not a signal that is visible at the terminals, the current- and voltage-control views are generally used in circuit design and analysis.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In analog circuit design, the current-control view is sometimes used because it is approximately linear.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] That is, the collector current is approximately $\beta _{\text{F}}$ times the base current.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Some basic circuits can be designed by assuming that the base–emitter voltage is approximately constant and that collector current is β times the base current.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] However, to accurately and reliably design production BJT circuits, the voltage-control model (e.g. the Ebers–Moll model) is required.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] For translinear circuits, in which the exponential I–V curve is key to the operation, the transistors are usually modeled as voltage-controlled current sources whose transconductance is proportional to their collector current.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In general, transistor-level circuit analysis is performed using SPICE or a comparable analog-circuit simulator, so mathematical model complexity is usually not of much concern to the designer, but a simplified view of the characteristics allows designs to be created following a logical process.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Bipolar transistors, and particularly power transistors, have long base-storage times when they are driven into saturation; the base storage limits turn-off time in switching applications.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] A Baker clamp can prevent the transistor from heavily saturating, which reduces the amount of charge stored in the base and thus improves switching time.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The proportion of carriers able to cross the base and reach the collector is a measure of the BJT efficiency.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The heavy doping of the emitter region and light doping of the base region causes many more electrons to be injected from the emitter into the base than holes to be injected from the base into the emitter.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] A thin and lightly doped base region means that most of the minority carriers that are injected into the base will diffuse to the collector and not recombine.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The *common-emitter current gain* is represented by βF or the h-parameter hFE; it is approximately the ratio of the collector's direct current to the base's direct current in forward-active region.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] (The F subscript is used to indicate the forward-active mode of operation.) It is typically greater than 50 for small-signal transistors, but can be smaller in transistors designed for high-power applications.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Both injection efficiency and recombination in the base reduce the BJT gain.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Another useful characteristic is the *common-base current gain*, αF.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The common-base current gain is approximately the gain of current from emitter to collector in the forward-active region.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] This ratio usually has a value close to unity; between 0.980 and 0.998.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] It is less than unity due to recombination of charge carriers as they cross the base region.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Beta is a convenient figure of merit to describe the performance of a bipolar transistor, but is not a fundamental physical property of the device.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Bipolar transistors can be considered voltage-controlled devices (fundamentally the collector current is controlled by the base–emitter voltage; the base current could be considered a defect and is controlled by the characteristics of the base–emitter junction and recombination in the base).
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In many designs beta is assumed high enough so that base current has a negligible effect on the circuit.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In some circuits (generally switching circuits), sufficient base current is supplied so that even the lowest beta value a particular device may have will still allow the required collector current to flow.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] BJTs consists of three differently doped semiconductor regions: the *emitter* region, the *base* region and the *collector* region.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] These regions are, respectively, *p* type, *n* type and *p* type in a PNP transistor, and *n* type, *p* type and *n* type in an NPN transistor.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Each semiconductor region is connected to a terminal, appropriately labeled: *emitter* (E), *base* (B) and *collector* (C).
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The *base* is physically located between the *emitter* and the *collector* and is made from lightly doped, high-resistivity material.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The collector surrounds the emitter region, making it almost impossible for the electrons injected into the base region to escape without being collected, thus making the resulting value of α very close to unity, and so, giving the transistor a large β.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] A cross-section view of a BJT indicates that the collector–base junction has a much larger area than the emitter–base junction.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The bipolar junction transistor, unlike other transistors, is usually not a symmetrical device.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] This means that interchanging the collector and the emitter makes the transistor leave the forward active mode and start to operate in reverse mode.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Because the transistor's internal structure is usually optimized for forward-mode operation, interchanging the collector and the emitter makes the values of α and β in reverse operation much smaller than those in forward operation; often the α of the reverse mode is lower than 0.5.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The lack of symmetry is primarily due to the doping ratios of the emitter and the collector.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The emitter is heavily doped, while the collector is lightly doped, allowing a large reverse bias voltage to be applied before the collector–base junction breaks down.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The collector–base junction is reverse biased in normal operation.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The reason the emitter is heavily doped is to increase the emitter injection efficiency: the ratio of carriers injected by the emitter to those injected by the base.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] For high current gain, most of the carriers injected into the emitter–base junction must come from the emitter.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The low-performance "lateral" bipolar transistors sometimes used in bipolar and MOS integrated circuits are sometimes designed symmetrically, that is, with no difference between forward and backward operation.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Small changes in the voltage applied across the base–emitter terminals cause the current between the *emitter* and the *collector* to change significantly.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] This effect can be used to amplify the input voltage or current.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] BJTs can be thought of as voltage-controlled current sources, but are more simply characterized as current-controlled current sources, or current amplifiers, due to the low impedance at the base.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Early transistors were made from germanium but most modern BJTs are made from silicon.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] A significant minority are also now made from gallium arsenide, especially for very high speed applications (see HBT, below).
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The heterojunction bipolar transistor (HBT) is an improvement of the BJT that can handle signals of very high frequencies up to several hundred GHz.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] It is common in modern ultrafast circuits, mostly RF systems.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Two commonly used HBTs are silicon–germanium and aluminum gallium arsenide, though a wide variety of semiconductors may be used for the HBT structure.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] HBT structures are usually grown by epitaxy techniques like MOCVD and MBE.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The base–emitter junction is forward biased and the base–collector junction is reverse biased.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] to the base current, but many times larger, for small base current variations.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] By reversing the biasing conditions of the forward-active region, a bipolar transistor goes into reverse-active mode.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In this mode, the emitter and collector regions switch roles.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] in inverted mode is several times smaller (2–3 times for the ordinary germanium transistor).
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The reverse bias breakdown voltage to the base may be an order of magnitude lower in this region.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] With both junctions forward biased, a BJT is in saturation mode and facilitates high current conduction from the emitter to the collector (or the other direction in the case of NPN, with negatively charged carriers flowing from emitter to collector).
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] This mode corresponds to a logical "on", or a closed switch.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In cut-off, biasing conditions opposite of saturation (both junctions reverse biased) are present.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] There is very little current, which corresponds to a logical "off", or an open switch.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Input and output characteristics for a common-base silicon transistor amplifier.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Although these regions are well defined for sufficiently large applied voltage, they overlap somewhat for small (less than a few hundred millivolts) biases.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The diagram shows a schematic representation of an NPN transistor connected to two voltage sources.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] (The same description applies to a PNP transistor with reversed directions of current flow and applied voltage.) This applied voltage causes the lower p–n junction to become forward biased, allowing a flow of electrons from the emitter into the base.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In active mode, the electric field existing between base and collector (caused by *V*CE) will cause the majority of these electrons to cross the upper p–n junction into the collector to form the collector current *I*C.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The remainder of the electrons recombine with holes, the majority carriers in the base, making a current through the base connection to form the base current, *I*B.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] As shown in the diagram, the emitter current, *I*E, is the total transistor current, which is the sum of the other terminal currents, (i.e.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In the diagram, the arrows representing current point in the direction of conventional current – the flow of electrons is in the opposite direction of the arrows because electrons carry negative electric charge.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In active mode, the ratio of the collector current to the base current is called the *DC current gain*.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] This gain is usually 100 or more, but robust circuit designs do not depend on the exact value (for example see op-amp).
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The value of this gain for DC signals is referred to as $h_{\text{FE}}$ , and the value of this gain for small signals is referred to as $h_{\text{fe}}$ .
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] That is, when a small change in the currents occurs, and sufficient time has passed for the new condition to reach a steady state $h_{\text{fe}}$ is the ratio of the change in collector current to the change in base current.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The symbol $\beta$ is used for both $h_{\text{FE}}$ and $h_{\text{fe}}$ .
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The emitter current is related to $V_{\text{BE}}$ exponentially.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] At room temperature, an increase in $V_{\text{BE}}$ by approximately 60 mV increases the emitter current by a factor of 10.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Because the base current is approximately proportional to the collector and emitter currents, they vary in the same way.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] BJTs can be thought of as two diodes (p–n junctions) sharing a common region that minority carriers can move through.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] A PNP BJT will function like two diodes that share an N-type cathode region, and the NPN like two diodes sharing a P-type anode region.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Connecting two diodes with wires will not make a BJT, since minority carriers will not be able to get from one p–n junction to the other through the wire.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Both types of BJT function by letting a small current input to the base control an amplified output from the collector.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The result is that the BJT makes a good switch that is controlled by its base input.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The BJT also makes a good amplifier, since it can multiply a weak input signal to about 100 times its original strength.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Networks of BJTs are used to make powerful amplifiers with many different applications.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In the discussion below, focus is on the NPN BJT.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In what is called active mode, the base–emitter voltage $V_{\text{BE}}$ and collector–base voltage $V_{\text{CB}}$ are positive, forward biasing the emitter–base junction and reverse-biasing the collector–base junction.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In this mode, electrons are injected from the forward biased n-type emitter region into the p-type base where they diffuse as minority carriers to the reverse-biased n-type collector and are swept away by the electric field in the reverse-biased collector–base junction.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] For an illustration of forward and reverse bias, see semiconductor diodes.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The $\alpha$ and forward $\beta$ parameters are as described previously.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] A reverse $\beta$ is sometimes included in the model.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The unapproximated Ebers–Moll equations used to describe the three currents in any operating region are given below.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] These equations are based on the transport model for a bipolar junction transistor.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] As the collector–base voltage ( $V_{\text{CB}}=V_{\text{CE}}-V_{\text{BE}}$ ) varies, the collector–base depletion region varies in size.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] An increase in the collector–base voltage, for example, causes a greater reverse bias across the collector–base junction, increasing the collector–base depletion region width, and decreasing the width of the base.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] This variation in base width often is called the *Early effect* after its discoverer James M.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Both factors increase the collector or "output" current of the transistor in response to an increase in the collector–base voltage.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] When the base–collector voltage reaches a certain (device-specific) value, the base–collector depletion region boundary meets the base–emitter depletion region boundary.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] When in this state the transistor effectively has no base.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The device thus loses all gain when in this state.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The Gummel–Poon model is a detailed charge-controlled model of BJT dynamics, which has been adopted and elaborated by others to explain transistor dynamics in greater detail than the terminal-based models typically do.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] This model also includes the dependence of transistor $\beta$ -values upon the direct current levels in the transistor, which are assumed current-independent in the Ebers–Moll model.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The hybrid-pi model is a popular circuit model used for analyzing the small signal and AC behavior of bipolar junction and field effect transistors.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Sometimes it is also called *Giacoletto model* because it was introduced by L.J.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The model can be quite accurate for low-frequency circuits and can easily be adapted for higher-frequency circuits with the addition of appropriate inter-electrode capacitances and other parasitic elements.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Another model commonly used to analyze BJT circuits is the *h-parameter* model, also known as the hybrid equivalent model, closely related to the hybrid-pi model and the y-parameter two-port, but using input current and output voltage as independent variables, rather than input and output voltages.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] This two-port network is particularly suited to BJTs as it lends itself easily to the analysis of circuit behavior, and may be used to develop further accurate models.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] As shown, the term *x* in the model represents a different BJT lead depending on the topology used.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] As shown, the h-parameters have lower-case subscripts and hence signify AC conditions or analyses.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] For DC conditions they are specified in upper-case.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] For the CE topology, an approximate h-parameter model is commonly used which further simplifies the circuit analysis.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] For this the *h*oe and *h*re parameters are neglected (that is, they are set to infinity and zero, respectively).
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The h-parameter model as shown is suited to low-frequency, small-signal analysis.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] For high-frequency analyses the inter-electrode capacitances that are important at high frequencies must be added.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The *h* refers to its being an h-parameter, a set of parameters named for their origin in a ***h**ybrid equivalent circuit* model (see above).
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] So hFE (or hFE) refers to the (total; DC) collector current divided by the base current, and is dimensionless.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] It is a parameter that varies somewhat with collector current, but is often approximated as a constant; it is normally specified at a typical collector current and voltage, or graphed as a function of collector current.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The Gummel–Poon SPICE model is often used, but it suffers from several limitations.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] For instance, reverse breakdown of the base–emitter diode is not captured by the SGP (SPICE Gummel–Poon) model, neither are thermal effects (self-heating) or quasi-saturation.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] These have been addressed in various more advanced models which either focus on specific cases of application (Mextram, HICUM, Modella) or are designed for universal usage (VBIC).
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] By convention, the direction of current on diagrams is shown as the direction in which a positive charge would move.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] However, in actuality, current in metal conductors is due to the flow of electrons.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Because electrons carry a negative charge, they move in the direction opposite to conventional current.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] On the other hand, inside a bipolar transistor, currents can be composed of both positively charged holes and negatively charged electrons.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] In this article, current arrows are shown in the conventional direction, but labels for the movement of holes and electrons show their actual direction inside the transistor.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The arrow on the symbol for bipolar transistors indicates the p–n junction between base and emitter and points in the direction in which conventional current travels.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The BJT remains a device that excels in some applications, such as discrete circuit design, due to the very wide selection of BJT types available, and because of its high transconductance and output resistance compared to MOSFETs.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The BJT is also the choice for demanding analog circuits, especially for very-high-frequency applications, such as radio-frequency circuits for wireless systems.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Bipolar transistors can be combined with MOSFETs in an integrated circuit by using a BiCMOS process of wafer fabrication to create circuits that take advantage of the application strengths of both types of transistor.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] One of the most prominent early uses of the transistor was in consumer products such as the transistor radio which began production in 1954.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The use of transistors in handheld radios and would also jumpstart a small Japanese company named Tokyo Tsushin Kogyo K.K. to prominence with its TR-55 transistor radio bearing the name the company would soon change to match: Sony.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The follow-on pocket-sized Sony TR-63 and several larger models by other manufacturers cemented the transistor and miniaturized electronics as critical to the new, portable consumer device market for decades to come.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] The transistor parameters α and β characterize the current gain of the BJT.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] It is this gain that allows BJTs to be used as the building blocks of electronic amplifiers.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Because of the known temperature and current dependence of the forward-biased base–emitter junction voltage, the BJT can be used to measure temperature by subtracting two voltages at two different bias currents in a known ratio.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Because base–emitter voltage varies as the logarithm of the base–emitter and collector–emitter currents, a BJT can also be used to compute logarithms and anti-logarithms.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] A diode can also perform these nonlinear functions but the transistor provides more circuit flexibility.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Transistors may be deliberately made with a lower collector to emitter breakdown voltage than the collector to base breakdown voltage.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] If the emitter–base junction is reverse biased the collector emitter voltage may be maintained at a voltage just below breakdown.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] As soon as the base voltage is allowed to rise, and current flows avalanche occurs and impact ionization in the collector base depletion region rapidly floods the base with carriers and turns the transistor fully on.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] So long as the pulses are short enough and infrequent enough that the device is not damaged, this effect can be used to create very sharp falling edges.
[src:hitac-s-810/bipolar-junction-transistor] Special avalanche transistor devices are made for this application.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] In 2010, Hitachi Data Systems sold through direct and indirect channels in more than 170 countries and regions, with customers that included over half of the Fortune 100 companies at the time.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] It was a subsidiary of Hitachi and part of the Hitachi Information Systems & Telecommunications Division until 2017.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] In 2017, it merged with Pentaho and Hitachi Insight Group to form Hitachi Vantara.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Itel was founded in 1967 by Peter Redfield and Gary Friedman as an equipment leasing company and initially focused on leasing IBM mainframes.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Through creative financial arrangements and investments, Itel began to lease IBM mainframes to customers at lower costs, which led to Itel ranking second to IBM in revenues.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] In 1977, a joint venture between National Semiconductor and Hitachi formed, and was contracted by Itel to manufacture IBM-compatible mainframes branded as Advanced Systems.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] After initial success shipping 200 such systems and net profits of $73 million, Itel increased investments and personnel to market its Advanced Systems brand.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] When Itel requested lower prices to compete with IBM, the CEO of National Semiconductor Charlie Sporck, persuaded Itel to commit to long-term contracts with National Semiconductor and Hitachi.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] When news leaked that IBM was releasing a superior line of computers, customers held back purchases of Itel goods, causing Itel's inventory to build up drastically.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Hitachi agreed to Itel's request to cut back on shipment, but National Semiconductor insisted that National had blackmailed Itel.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] In 1979, Redfield was forced to resign as CEO.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] National Semiconductor took over Itel Advanced Systems' sales and marketing divisions.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] National Semiconductor renamed the National Advanced Systems (NAS) division, assembling and selling IBM-compatibles where the central processing unit (CPU) was imported from Hitachi.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] National and Hitachi relied upon IBM's gradual and restrained roll-out of newer models to support IBM's technology and market share, which supported NAS's occasional successes.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] National Semiconductor and its subsidiary NAS were sued in 1983 by IBM for $2.5 billion on charges of using computer technology secrets stolen from IBM, as the result of an investigation by the United States Government into National's collaboration with Hitachi.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Hitachi settled with IBM and licensed the mainframe operating system software from IBM.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] In 1983, NAS ceased manufacturing its line of mainframes (which had Hitachi processors) and became a reseller of Hitachi's mainframe and data storage products.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems (HDS) was founded in 1989 when Hitachi and Electronic Data Systems (EDS) acquired National Advanced Systems (NAS) from National Semiconductor and renamed it Hitachi Data Systems.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Before that, the origins of the company had a history that stretched back to Itel, an early player in the mainframe market.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Intel's Computer Products Group sold National Semiconductors' IBM plug compatible mainframes.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] In 1979 National Semiconductor took over Itel and formed National Advanced Systems (NAS).
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] NAS shifted from manufacturing mainframes and began marketing systems from Hitachi.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] In 1999, Hitachi bought out EDS's share, and HDS became a wholly owned subsidiary of Hitachi.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] For many years, HDS sold Hitachi IBM plug-compatible mainframes and storage systems, but in 2000, it exited the mainframe business and shifted its focus to enterprise storage.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] On February 28, 1989, National Semiconductor and Hitachi announced their agreement that Hitachi and Electronic Data Systems (EDS) would jointly acquire NAS for $398 million in cash, of which Hitachi would own 80%.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Memorex Telex and National had earlier, on January 10, 1989, announced plans on a joint venture "under which each company would own half of the unit and National would get $250 million plus four million shares of Memorex Telex".
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] By that time, Memorex Telex was able to arrange financing for the deal, but National had already accepted the Hitachi–EDS deal.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] The acquisition was envisaged to provide Hitachi with a better presence in the United States to compete with IBM.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] The entity was renamed Hitachi Data Systems (HDS).
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] On January 29, 1999, Hitachi announced it would take over EDS' stake in HDS, appointing Jun Naruse as CEO of its new subsidiary.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Naruse was an engineer with the RAID Systems Division who was involved in developing storage systems.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Having total control of the company, Hitachi infused Hitachi Data Systems with its corporate culture, ethics, and practices.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] On April 6, 2000, Hitachi Data Systems announced a re-organization to focus on storage systems rather than mainframes.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Shortly thereafter (June 26, 2000), the first HDS storage product was unveiled, the Freedom Storage Lightning 9900, featuring the crossbar switched architecture to interconnect memory, disks, servers, and other external devices instead of the traditional bus architecture.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] In addition to HDS sales, HP OEM’d and Sun resold the 9900 and succeeding generations, which had additional capabilities such as virtualization of external Hitachi and third-party storage systems to form storage pools.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] In January 2001, HDS announced the Thunder 9200, a mid-range modular storage system aimed at the small and medium business market, sold mainly through resellers.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems high-end and mid-range modular storage systems were complemented by software for storage management, content management, business continuity, replication, data protection, and IT operations.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] In 2002, Hitachi acquired Comstock Systems Corp, and analysts estimated that the acquisition would lead to a 35% percent market share.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] HDS moved to use the term cloud computing, culminating with an announcement on October 25, 2011.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] In August 2014, in partnership with Avnet, HDS announced cloud partners.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] The corporate headquarters are in Santa Clara, California, with business offices in the United States, Australia and New Zealand, Canada, Latin America, Europe, the Middle East, and Africa.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] The culture of Hitachi Vantara is influenced by the values of Hitachi: wa (harmony, trust, and respect), Makoto (integrity, honesty), and kaitakusha-seishin (pioneering spirit and challenges).
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems appeared in *Fortune* magazine's "100 Best Companies to Work For" list in 2012, 2013 and 2014 and was ranked No.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] 8 in the *Fortune* list of top-paying companies in 2012.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Chief Executive Magazine gave HDS a ranking of No.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] 16 in its “40 Best Companies for Leaders” list for 2012.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems was recognized among the "Best Companies to Work For" in France and Poland in 2011.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] In 2010 Hitachi Data Systems was accredited by the Best Companies organization in the United Kingdom.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Synchronous TrueCopy causes each write to the primary volume to be performed to the secondary as well, and the I/O is considered complete only when updates to both primary and secondary have been completed.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Asynchronous TrueCopy stores time-stamped IO packets in the primary disk array and transfers them to the secondary array subject to link bandwidth.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] When the primary array's buffer is exhausted, it starts flagging tracks on the primary to be duplicated to the secondary when bandwidth permits.
[src:hitac-s-810/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems has four types of partners: Technology, Global Systems Integrators, Hitachi TrueNorth Partners, and Hitachi TrueNorth Advisor Partners.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The **HITAC S-810** is a family of vector supercomputers developed, manufactured and marketed by Hitachi.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The S-810, first announced in August 1982, was the second Japanese supercomputer, following the Fujitsu VP-200 (July 1982) but predating the NEC SX-2 (April 1983).
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The S-810 was Hitachi's first supercomputer, although the company had previously built a vector processor, the IAP.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The first system shipped was a top-end S-810/20 model, which was delivered to the University of Tokyo's Large Computer Center in October 1983.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The S-810 was succeeded as Hitachi's top-end supercomputer by the HITAC S-820 announced in July 1987.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The S-810 implements a Hitachi-designed extension of the IBM System/370 instruction set architecture with 83 vector instructions (80 in the S-810/5 and S-810/10).
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The vector instructions are *register-to-register*, meaning that they do not directly reference memory.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The scalar processor is a Hitachi HITAC M-280H mainframe with a 28 nanosecond (ns) cycle time (clock rate of approximately 35.71 MHz).
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] In the S-810/20, there are 32 scalar registers, whereas the other models have 16.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] In all models, the scalar processor has a large 256 kilobyte cache.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The vector processor has a 14 ns cycle time (clock rate of approximately 71.43 MHz).
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The vector registers are 256 elements wide, and each element is 64 bits wide.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The S-810/20 has 32 of these registers, whereas the other models have 16.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] These registers are implemented with 1 kilobit (Kbit) bipolar RAM integrated circuits (ICs) with a 4.5 ns access time.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] All models have eight 256-bit vector mask registers and 48 vector address registers.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] All models have three load pipelines and one load/store pipeline for accessing the main memory.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The S-810/20 has two lanes, each with two add, one multiply followed by add, and one multiply or divide followed by add floating point pipelines, for a total of twelve.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The S-810/10 has one lane with the same configuration as the S-810/20 and therefore a total of six pipelines.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] CPU logic is implemented with two emitter-coupled logic gate array IC types, a 550-gate part with a 250 picosecond (ps) gate delay and a 1,500-gate part with a 450 ps gate delay.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The main memory is implemented with 16 Kbit complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor static random access memory ICs with an access time of 40 ns.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] The S-810/20 supports 64 to 256 megabyte (MB) of main memory, whereas the other models support 32 to 128 MB.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] They differ in the number of vector pipelines installed, the number of scalar registers, the number vector registers, and the amount of memory supported.
[src:hitac-s-810/hitac-s-810] Hitachi claimed that the S-810/5's peak performance was 160 MFLOPS, the S-810/10's was 315 MFLOPS, and the S-810/20's was 630 MFLOPS.
